Image Tagging and Registry Interaction
Objectives
By the end of this lab, you will be able to:

Tag container images with semantic versioning
Authenticate with container registries (Docker Hub or private)
Push and pull images from registries
Understand tag immutability and image digests
Prerequisites
Podman installed (version 3.0+)
A Docker Hub account (or access to a private registry)
Basic familiarity with Linux command line
Internet access
Lab Tasks
Task 1: Tagging Images Semantically
Objective: Learn to apply meaningful tags to container images

List existing images:

podman images
Tag an existing image:

podman tag <source_image> <new_name>:<tag>
Example:

podman tag docker.io/library/nginx my-nginx:v1.0
Verify the new tag:

podman images | grep nginx
Expected Output: You should see both the original nginx image and your newly tagged version.

Key Concept: Tags should follow semantic versioning (vMAJOR.MINOR.PATCH) for production images.

Task 2: Logging into a Registry
Objective: Authenticate with Docker Hub or private registry

Login to Docker Hub:

podman login docker.io
Enter your Docker Hub username and password when prompted.

Verify login:

podman info | grep -A 5 "registries"
Troubleshooting Tip: If using a private registry, replace docker.io with your registry URL.

Task 3: Pushing Images to Registry
Objective: Upload your tagged image to a registry

Tag image with registry prefix:

podman tag my-nginx:v1.0 docker.io/<your_username>/my-nginx:v1.0
Push the image:

podman push docker.io/<your_username>/my-nginx:v1.0
Verify on Docker Hub:

Log in to Docker Hub web interface
Check your repository for the pushed image
Expected Outcome: Image appears in your Docker Hub repository.

Task 4: Pulling Images from Registry
Objective: Download images from a registry

Remove local image:

podman rmi docker.io/<your_username>/my-nginx:v1.0
Pull the image:

podman pull docker.io/<your_username>/my-nginx:v1.0
Verify the download:

podman images
Key Concept: Pulling always fetches the image associated with the tag at that moment.

Task 5: Understanding Tag Immutability and Digests
Objective: Learn about image digests and tag behavior

Inspect image digest:

podman inspect --format '{{.Digest}}' docker.io/<your_username>/my-nginx:v1.0
Pull by digest:

podman pull docker.io/<your_username>/my-nginx@<digest>
Test tag immutability:

Push a new image with same tag
Notice how the digest changes
Explanation: While tags can be reassigned, digests are immutable identifiers for specific image versions.

Conclusion
In this lab, you've learned essential skills for working with container images and registries:

Applied semantic versioning to image tags
Authenticated with container registries
Pushed and pulled images
Understood the importance of digests and tag immutability
These skills form the foundation for efficient container image management in production environments.

